Here's how to implement all three:

**1 & 2. Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`** — use `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

Key points:
- `GetDeferral()` is **required** for async checks — without it the navigation completes before your `await` finishes.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- Check `ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so the guard only fires on back-navigation.

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button** — add this in `EditProductPage.xaml`:

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

The `Command` fires instead of the default back navigation, so your ViewModel can run its own logic:

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes", "Discard changes?", "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

> **Note:** The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the default back action entirely — you must call `GoToAsync("..")` yourself. The `OnNavigating` guard covers the hardware/gesture back; the `CancelCommand` covers the toolbar button. Together they handle all back-navigation paths.
